properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The first heat event of the season continues this evening and will last through Tuesday. Temperatures will reach 29 degrees Celsius this evening, before falling to 18 degrees Celsius tonight. Temperatures on Tuesday will reach 29 degrees Celsius again before a cooler air mass moves in to the region. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First heat event of the year expected Tuesday through Wednesday. A hot airmass approaching the area will bring daytime temperatures in the low thirties over the next couple of days. With increasing humidity on Wednesday, humidex values are expected to creep in the mid to high thirties. Lows between 20 and 22 degrees Celsius are also expected Tuesday night. Temperatures will cool off Wednesday night as Tropical Depression Cristobal approaches Ontario. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Flood Watch Is Being Issued For Northwestern Manitoba.
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Watch for Northwestern Manitoba due to expected high flows as a result of recent and expected precipitation. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing water or waters of unknown depth. Use caution when driving on all roads, as road conditions may have changed. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions issued by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca Follow @MBGov and @MBGovRoads on Twitter or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2020-06-09T17:00:00-05:00

properties.Title: Update To Civil Emergency Alert Issued By Government Of Saskatchewan
properties.Summary:
Description: Update for the Civil Emergency Alert issued by the Government of Saskatchewan. The state of emergency in Saskatchewan remains in effect. UPDATE: Phase 3 of Re-Open Saskatchewan is effective June 8. Allowable maximum for public and private gatherings has been increased to 15 inside and 30 outside. The allowable businesses and services identified in Phase 3 can operate up to 50 percent capacity of their regular total capacity. Physical distancing by at least two metres from others is to be applied in all public and private gatherings. UPDATE for Northwest Region. The public health order restricting travel for Northwest Saskatchewan is lifted, allowing for travel in and out of the northwest region, and between communities. At this time and until further notice, Phase 3 of the Re-Open Saskatchewan plan is delayed across all of the Northwest region of the province.
Expires: 2020-06-15T17:00:00-06:00

Area: Province of Saskatchewan
